# **Appendix B2: POC — VHD Lift ****&**** Shift via Azure Portal (GUI)**

This section documents the same Node5 VHD Lift & Shift migration performed using the Azure Portal graphical interface instead of Azure CLI. Both approaches produce identical results. Use the CLI approach for automation and repeatability; use the Portal approach for one-time migrations or when learning the Azure resource model visually.

## **B2.1 Pre-Requisites**

- VHD file already uploaded to Azure Blob Storage (ushacloudmigrationncus / vhds container)

- Active Azure Subscription with Contributor access

- Browser open to portal.azure.com

## **B2.2 Step 1 — Create Storage Account (if not already exists)**

- In Azure Portal, search for Storage accounts in the top search bar

- Click + Create

- Fill in: Subscription = Azure subscription 1, Resource Group = UshacloudMigration1

- Storage account name = ushacloudmigrationncus

- Region = (US) North Central US

- Performance = Standard, Redundancy = Locally-redundant storage (LRS)

- Click Review + Create, then Create

- Once deployed, go to the storage account and click Containers under Data Storage

- Click + Container, name it vhds, set access level to Private, click Create

**NOTE: **Screenshots: Storage account creation form, container creation dialog, container listed in portal.

## **B2.3 Step 2 — Upload VHD to Blob Container**

- Navigate to the vhds container inside ushacloudmigrationncus

- Click Upload

- Click Browse for files and select Node5_Fixed_Final.vhd from local disk

- Expand Advanced options — set Blob type to Page blob (required for VHDs)

- Click Upload and wait for completion (64 GiB may take significant time depending on connection)

- Alternatively use AzCopy for faster upload:

azcopy copy 'C:\VMs\Node5_Fixed_Final.vhd' \

  'https://ushacloudmigrationncus.blob.core.windows.net/vhds/Node5_Fixed_Final.vhd' \

  --blob-type PageBlob

**NOTE: **Screenshots: Upload dialog with Page blob selected, blob listed in container after upload.

## **B2.4 Step 3 — Create Managed Disk from VHD**

- In Azure Portal, search for Disks in the top search bar

- Click + Create

- Fill in Project Details: Subscription = Azure subscription 1, Resource Group = UshacloudMigration1

- Under Disk Details: Disk name = disk-node5-os-ncus

- Region = (US) North Central US

- Availability zone = No infrastructure redundancy required

- Source type = Storage blob

- Source subscription = Azure subscription 1

- Source blob = Browse and select the VHD: https://ushacloudmigrationncus.blob.core.windows.net/vhds/Node5_Fixed_Final.vhd

- OS type = Windows

- VM generation = Generation 1

- VM architecture = x64

- Click Change size — IMPORTANT: Change Storage type from Premium SSD v2 to Standard SSD (locally-redundant storage)

- Select 64 GiB (E6 tier) and click OK

- Click Review + Create, then Create

- Wait for deployment to complete — Provisioning state will show Succeeded

**NOTE: **Screenshots: Disk creation form filled in, Storage type dropdown showing Standard SSD selected, 64 GiB E6 highlighted, Review + Create summary, Deployment succeeded.

## **B2.5 Step 4 — Create Network Security Group**

- In Azure Portal, search for Network security groups

- Click + Create

- Resource Group = UshacloudMigration1, Name = nsg-sqlnode5-ncus, Region = North Central US

- Click Review + Create, then Create

- Once deployed, open the NSG and click Inbound security rules

- Click + Add — add RDP rule: Port 3389, Protocol TCP, Action Allow, Priority 1000, Name Allow-RDP

- Click + Add — add SQL rule: Port 1433, Protocol TCP, Action Allow, Priority 1010, Name Allow-SQL

**NOTE: **Screenshots: NSG creation form, inbound rules list showing Allow-RDP and Allow-SQL rules.

## **B2.6 Step 5 — Create Virtual Machine from Managed Disk**

- In Azure Portal, search for Virtual machines

- Click + Create, then Azure virtual machine

- Basics tab: Subscription = Azure subscription 1, Resource Group = UshacloudMigration1

- Virtual machine name = vm-sqlnode5-azure, Region = (US) North Central US

- Availability options = No infrastructure redundancy required

- Image = Click See all images — search for the managed disk option. Select No image required (use existing disk)

- Under Disks tab: OS disk — click Attach an existing disk, select disk-node5-os-ncus

- Size = Click See all sizes, search for Standard_B2as_v2, select it

- Under Networking tab: Virtual network — create new or select existing VNet in NCUS

- NIC network security group = Advanced, select nsg-sqlnode5-ncus

- Public IP = Create new, name pip-sqlnode5

- Click Review + Create, verify summary, click Create

- Wait for deployment — VM will appear as Running in Virtual machines list

**NOTE: **Screenshots: VM creation Basics tab, Disks tab showing managed disk attached, Networking tab with NSG selected, Deployment in progress, VM running status showing public IP.

## **B2.7 Step 6 — Connect via RDP**

- In Azure Portal, navigate to vm-sqlnode5-azure

- Click Connect at the top, then select RDP

- Click Download RDP File

- Open the downloaded .rdp file

- Enter Node5 local administrator credentials when prompted

- Accept any certificate warnings — click Yes to connect

- Once logged in, open SQL Server Management Studio (SSMS)

- Connect to localhost or the server name

- Verify both databases are online:

SELECT name, state_desc FROM sys.databases

WHERE name IN ('CoreBank_OnPrem_POC', 'AcquiredBanks_OnPrem_POC');

-- Expected result: ONLINE for both

**NOTE: **Screenshots: Azure Portal Connect RDP blade, RDP login prompt, SSMS connected to Azure VM, databases showing ONLINE in sys.databases query results.

## **B2.8 GUI vs CLI Comparison**

| **Step** | **GUI (Azure Portal)** | **CLI (Azure Cloud Shell)** |
| --- | --- | --- |
| Storage Account | Portal form — 8 fields to fill | az storage account create — 1 command |
| Blob Container | Click + Container in portal | az storage container create — 1 command |
| VHD Upload | Upload button — manual file browse | azcopy — automated, faster for large files |
| SAS Token | Portal: Storage > Shared access signature blade | az storage blob generate-sas — 1 command |
| Cross-region copy | Not easily done in Portal UI — requires AzCopy or CLI | az storage blob copy start — 1 command |
| Disk creation | Portal form — must manually change disk type from SSD v2 | az disk create with --sku StandardSSD_LRS — explicit |
| NSG + Rules | Portal: 3 separate create operations via UI | 3 CLI commands — scriptable and repeatable |
| VM creation | Portal wizard — 5 tabs to navigate | az vm create — 1 command with all params |
| Error handling | Errors shown as red banners in portal | Errors returned as JSON with error codes |
| Repeatability | Manual — not easily repeatable | Fully scriptable — can be run as pipeline |

**NOTE: **Recommendation: Use the GUI approach for learning and one-time migrations. Use the CLI approach for production pipelines, automation, and when migrating multiple servers.

